{"id":"2202.03821","submitter":"Eric Ufferman","authors":"Eric Ufferman, Nicolas Swanson","title":"A Lower Bound on the Failed Zero Forcing Number of a Graph","comments":"11 pages, 13 figures. Comments welcome","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Given a graph $G=(V,E)$ and a set of vertices marked as filled, we consider a\ncolor-change rule known as zero forcing. A set $S$ is a zero forcing set if\nfilling $S$ and applying all possible instances of the color change rule causes\nall vertices in $V$ to be filled. A failed zero forcing set is a set of\nvertices that is not a zero forcing set. Given a graph $G$, the failed zero\nforcing number $F(G)$ is the maximum size of a failed zero forcing set. An open\nquestion was whether given any $k$ there is a an $\\ell$ such that all graphs\nwith at least $\\ell$ vertices must satisfy $F(G)\\geq k$. We answer this\nquestion affirmatively by proving that for a graph $G$ with $n$ vertices,\n$F(G)\\geq \\lfloor\\frac{n-1}{2}\\rfloor$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 8 Feb 2022 12:33:25 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-02-09"}
